Historically Republicans have won through the electoral college. While there is a clear social upheaval due to coronavirus, unemployment and racial divides which have rallied people to demand change, the electoral college still remains exactly the same. This creates an uphill battle for Democrats who need to flip red states. In a time of uncertainty some voters may vote for what they know. In addition, the worldwide push( especially European countries) towards nationalism and right wing extremist propaganda creates a larger narrative for people in this age of social media and technology. These platforms allow for extremist groups to connect and mobilize. Especially with lockdowns in place, and large scale government involvement on day to day activities at the state and federal level these groups may surge to rise in the vote as a shocking underbelly of the population. Overall, the odds are in favor of Biden who has proven to follow traditional lines of the Democratic Party separating himself from more socialist and far left policies and as a middle ground, president for all. To say he is in the clear however would be an underestimation of voter potential.

Polls are indicating a blowout. Before I hear anyone say "But 2016 polls...", I need to clarify the fog of truth for some. 2016 polls were one of the most accurate in presidential polling history. They forecasted Clinton by 3.3%, she won by 2%, a very low polling error. She just didn't win the EC. The models for the EC were what was off, not the polling. Do not conflate the two. https://www.aapor.org/Education-Resources/Reports/An-Evaluation-of-2016-Election-Polls-in-the-U-S.aspx
Multiple models seem to indicate that Biden is the likely winner (80%+ likelihood). While a Trump win through the electoral college remains possible, it is fairly unlikely at this point.
Leaning on 538 conditional probabilities of Biden and Trump winning popular vote and winning electoral college: https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/2020-election-forecast/

538 gives Biden a 95% chance of winning the popular vote, Trump 5%. 538 also gives the odds of Biden losing the EC conditional on him winning the popular vote at 8%. 538 says that Trump's essentially guaranteed to win the EC if he wins the popular vote, so we can ignore that. Finally, the odds that the winner of the popular vote also wins the EC is 95*(1-.08)+5*(1-0)=92.4%.

A bit late to this forecast, but I have been forecasting the outcome of the Presidential election. Out of the last 58 elections, 53 Presidents won both the electoral college and popular vote so the base rate for p(PV win & EC win) = 0.914. Biden is favored in the polls and will likely win the popular vote. Using a conservative 80% probability of a Biden popular vote win from 538, my estimates are around 98% for this question. Also, qualitatively integrating opinions from @Balzac @cafebedouin and @LokiOdinevich. I think the crowd is underestimating the probability of this question, which may be due to the availability bias/heuristic where people tend to overestimate the likelihood of information/ events that are more easily recalled and/or more recent (e.g., the recent 2000 and 2016 elections with EC win != PV win).

As of yesterday, 270towins polling and consensus maps showed Biden with 262 and 278 electoral seats either safe or leaning Dem, respectively. Compared with Trump's 119 and 169 seats classified as safe or leaning Rep, this is a fairly decisive statement. If the consensus is correct, Biden doesn't need to win a single toss-up state to win the election (though it is unlikely he would bat 0% given his strong performances in each of the 5 so far). The polling map is bleaker, but still shows Biden needing only 8 points to pass the 270 threshold, which is again very doable given his current status in 'toss-up' states. Interestingly, polling actually has Texas classified as a toss-up, and a Dem victory there would mean an EC victory overall was all but certain. Biden is also up by a fair margin in virtually all non-partisan (and even most partisan) polls around the nation, suggesting he is the candidate more likely to take the popular vote. Given those two scenarios, it seems fairly likely that either (a) things will hold and Biden will take both or (b) Trump will find a way to bring voters to his side en masse, potentially taking both the popular vote and EC as well.

Let's look first at calculating a base rate. The winner of the Electoral College has won the popular vote in 53 out of the 58 US Presidential elections ever held - 91.3 percent. [1] Of course, last time around, this did not happen. It is one of the only four elections when this did not occur. The real insight here comes if we look a little further. Of the the elections held immediately following (1880, 1892, 2004) for which we have results, the incumbent president or his party went on to win twice (66%).[2]. How does this compare to overall incumbent advantage? Nineteen presidents have sought re-election since 1900 and only 5 (Bush Sr, Carter, Ford, Hoover and Taft) have lost. This gives the incumbent a a 73 percent chance of winning on average, slightly more than the previous statistic. [3] These are extraordinary times however and only one of the five Presidents to run for re-election during a recession has won (20%).[4] Obviously, the question is not "Will Trump get re-elected?" but it is still a statstic worthy of note in trying to calculate a base rate.

I collected the electoral college (EC) and popular vote (PV) shares for presidential elections since 1876. Finding this data took some effort as the above links didn't easily show what I wanted. I then used simple linear regression and found that the popular vote explains approximately 75% of the observed variance in the EC%. I then used a 2 x 2 matrix to determine the probability of winning the necessary # of EC votes, given that a candidate had >50% of the PV share. The data I have shows that: prob(EC>50%|PV>50%) = 79%.

I’ll start with a base rate of between 8-17% for a split. Since 1824, when the popular vote was first tallied, there have been 49 presidential elections. Of those, 4 clearly resulted in a split between popular vote winner and Electoral College winner, a 5th—the 1824 election—arguably resulted in such a difference, although in that election, no one received sufficient Electoral College votes and the election was decided in the House of Representatives. Possibly a 6th instance occurred if one counts the 1960 election and its Alabama discrepancies. That translates to about 8-12%. In contemporary, post World War II history, there have been 18 elections since 1948. Of those, 2 (and possibly 3, again accounting for the 1960 election) have resulted in a popular/electoral college vote split. That’s 11-17%. So let’s blend them and call the base 14%.
